(229, 37, 'DAY 1 09Colosseum (Monument, 12 €)', '<p><strong>09Colosseum (Monument, 12 &euro;)</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Why visit: Iconic symbol of Imperial Rome,One of the most visited tourist attractions in Rome and the World</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The Colosseum or Coliseum, also known as the Flavian Amphitheatre (Latin: Amphitheatrum Flavium; Italian: Anfiteatro Flavio or Colosseo) is an elliptical amphitheatre in the centre of the city of Rome, Italy. Built of concrete and stone, it was the largest amphitheatre of the Roman Empire, and is considered one of the greatest works of Roman architecture and engineering. It is the largest amphitheatre in the world.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Colosseum is situated just east of the Roman Forum. Construction began under the emperor Vespasian in 70 AD, and was completed in 80 AD under his successor and heir Titus. Further modifications were made during the reign of Domitian (81&ndash;96). These three emperors are known as the Flavian dynasty, and the amphitheatre was named in Latin for its association with their family name (Flavius).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>1Arch of Constantine (Monument, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit:Majestic monument,Symbol of victory</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The Arch of Constantine (Italian: Arco di Costantino) is a triumphal arch in Rome, situated between the Colosseum and the Palatine Hill. It was erected by the Roman Senate to commemorate Constantine Is victory over Maxentius at the Battle of Milvian Bridge on October 28, 312. Dedicated in 315, it is the latest of the existing triumphal arches in Rome, and the only one to make extensive use of spolia, re-using several majorreliefs from 2nd century imperial monuments, which give a striking and famous stylistic contrast to the sculpture newly created for the arch.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Roman Forum and Palatine Hill (Monument, 12 &euro;)</p>\n<p>Why visit: &nbsp;Center of the ancient world,One of the most ancient parts of the city,A great history lesson</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The Palatine Hill (Latin: Collis Palatium or Mons Palatinus) is the centermost of the Seven Hills of Rome and is one of the most ancient parts of thecity. It stands 40 metres above the Forum Romanum, looking down upon it on one side, and upon the Circus Maximus on the other.It is the etymological origin of the word "palace" and its cognates in other languages (Italian "Palazzo", French "Palais", German "Palast", etc.).</p>\n<p>0Piazza Venezia (Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit Focal point of modern Rome,Imposing monument of Italian Unification</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Piazza Venezia is a major circus and the central hub of Rome, Italy, in which many thoroughfares intersect, like Via dei Fori Imperiali and Via del Corso. It takes its name from Venice ("Venezia" in Italian), after the Venetian Cardinal, Pietro Barbo (later Pope Paul II) who had built Palazzo Venezia, a palace set next to church of Saint Mark, also nearby, the patron saint of Venice. Palazzo Venezia was the former embassy of the city of the Republic of Venice to Rome.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>15:50-16:20</p>\n<p>Vittorio Emanuele II Monument(Monument, 7 &euro;)</p>\n<p>Why visit Spectacular view of Rome Imposing memorial building</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The Altare della Patria (Altar of the Fatherland) also known as the Monumento Nazionale a Vittorio Emanuele II (National Monument to Victor Emmanuel II) or "Il Vittoriano" is a controversial monument built in honour of Victor Emmanuel, the first king of a unified Italy, located in Rome, Italy. It occupies a site between the Piazza Venezia and the Capitoline Hill.The eclectic structure was designed by Giuseppe Sacconi in 1885; sculpture for it was parceled out to established sculptors all over Italy, such as Leonardo Bistolfi and Angelo Zanelli. It was inaugurated in 1911 and completed in 1925</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>1Pantheon (Monument, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit The worlds largest unreinforced concrete dome One of the best preserved Roman buildings</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The building is circular with a portico of large granite Corinthian columns (eight in the first rank and two groups of four behind) under a pediment. A rectangular vestibule links the porch to the rotunda, which is under a coffered concrete dome, with a central opening (oculus) to the sky. Almost two thousand years after it was built, the Pantheons dome is still the worlds largest unreinforced concrete dome.[3] The height to the oculus and the diameter of the interior circle are the same, 43.3 meters (142 ft)&nbsp;</p>\n<p>1</p>\n<p>Trevi Fountain (Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit One of the most familiar sights of Rome A romantic spot</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Trevi Fountain (Italian: Fontana di Trevi) is a fountain in the Trevi district in Rome, Italy, designed by Italian architect Nicola Salvi and completed by Pietro Bracci. Standing 26.3 metres (86 ft) high and 49.15 metres (161.3 ft) wide, it is the largest Baroque fountain in the city and one of the most famous fountains in the world. The fountain has appeared in several notable films, including Federico Fellinis La Dolce Vita and is a popular tourist attraction.</p>\n<p>1</p>\n<p>Spanish Steps (Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit Romes most beloved Rococo monumentA well-known symbol of Rome</p>\n<p>The Spanish Steps (Italian: Scalinata della Trinit&agrave; dei Monti) are a set of steps in Rome, Italy, climbing a steep slope between the Piazza di Spagna at the base and Piazza Trinit&agrave; dei Monti, dominated by the Trinit&agrave; dei Monti church at the top. The Scalinata is the widest staircase in Europe.[1]</p>\n<p>The monumental stairway of 135 steps was built with French diplomat &Eacute;tienne Gueffier&rsquo;s bequeathed funds of 20,000 scudi, in 1723&ndash;1725, linking theBourbon Spanish Embassy, and the Trinit&agrave; dei Monti church that was under the patronage of the Bourbon kings of France, both located above &mdash; to theHoly See in Palazzo Monaldeschi located below. The stairway was designed by architects Francesco de Sanctis and Alessandro Specchi.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>END OF DAY 1</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '54cc83d917141day1.jpg'),
(230, 37, 'DAY 2', '<p>0St. Peters Basilica (Church, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit Largest Christian church in the world Sublime view of the city Home to Michelangelos Pieta</p>\n<p>st. Peters Basilica (Latin: Basilica Sancti Petri; Italian: Basilica di San Pietro in Vaticano) is a Late Renaissance church located within Vatican City.Designed principally by Donato Bramante, Michelangelo, Carlo Maderno and Gian Lorenzo Bernini, St. Peters is the most renowned work of Renaissance architecture[1] and remains one of the largest churches in the world.[2] While it is neither the mother church of the Roman Catholic Church nor the cathedral of the Bishop of Rome, St. Peters is regarded as one of the holiest Catholic sites. It has been described as "holding a unique position in the Christian world"[3] and as "the greatest of all churches oof Christendom"</p>\n<p>By Roman Catholic tradition, the basilica is the burial site of its namesake Saint Peter, one of the twelve apostles of Jesus</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>0Piazza di San Pietro(Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit One of the best known squares in the world Impressive design of Bernini</p>\n<p>The open space which lies before the basilica was redesigned by Gian Lorenzo Bernini from 1656 to 1667, under the direction of Pope Alexander VII, as an appropriate forecourt, designed "so that the greatest number of people could see the Pope give his blessing, either from the middle of the fa&ccedil;ade of the church or from a window in the Vatican Palace" (Norwich 1975 p 175). Bernini had been working on the interior of St. Peters for decades; now he gave order to the space with his renowned colonnades, using the Tuscan form of Doric, the simplest order in the classical vocabulary, not to compete with the palace-like fa&ccedil;ade by Carlo Maderno, but he employed it on an unprecedented colossal scale to suit the space and evoke emotions of awe.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Vatican Museums (Museum, 15 &euro;)</p>\n<p>Why visit</p>\n<p>One of the most known museums in the world</p>\n<p>Fabulous collection</p>\n<p>The Vatican Museums (Italian: Musei Vaticani) are the museums of the Vatican City and are located within the citys boundaries. They display works from the immense collection built up by the Roman Catholic Church throughout the centuries including some of the most renowned classical sculptures and most important masterpieces of Renaissance art in the world.</p>\n<p>Pope Julius II founded the museums in the early 16th century. The Sistine Chapel with its ceiling decorated by Michelangelo and the Stanze della Segnatura decorated by Raphael are on the visitor route through the Vatican Museums. They were visited by 4,310,083 people in the year 2007.[1]The Vatican Museums broke attendance records in 2011 with just over 5 million people.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Castel Sant Angelo (Museum, 8 &euro;)</p>\n<p>Why visit</p>\n<p>Magnificent historical monument</p>\n<p>Breathtaking views</p>\n<p>Castel SantAngelo (o Mole Adrianorum o "Castellum Crescentii" nel X-XII sec.), detto anche Mausoleo di Adriano, &egrave; un monumento diRoma, collegato allo Stato del Vaticano attraverso il corridoio fortificato del "passetto". Il castello &egrave; stato radicalmente modificato pi&ugrave; volte in epoca medioevale e rinascimentale situato sulla sponda destra del Tevere, di fronte al pons Aelius (attuale ponte SantAngelo) a poca distanza del Vaticano, nel rione di Borgo.</p>\n<p>Piazza Navona(Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit</p>\n<p>One of the most beautiful squares in Rome</p>\n<p>Great place for people watching</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Campo dei Fiori(Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit</p>\n<p>Lively square</p>\n<p>Great market</p>\n<p>Busy evening atmosphere</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p>1Jewish Ghetto (Park and outdoors, Free)</p>\n<p>Why visit</p>\n<p>Charming and eclectic neighborhood</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A collection of hidden gems</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '54cc83fecf86dday2.jpg'),
(231, 44, 'DAY 1: Zurich airport.', '<p>Zurich airport.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Arrive in Zurich airport our agent /driver receive in airport than transferred to hotel after refreshment (depends the arriving time)</p>\n<p>View the spectacular Rhine Falls in Schaffhausen&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;We proceed to Schaffhausen to visit the Rhine Falls-the largest waterfalls in Europe. This location has been specially chosen for you to get a real feel of Switzerland between the cantons of Schaffhausen and Z&uuml;rich. After dinner overnight stay in hotel</p>', '54cc8b0fa5467day1.jpg'),
(232, 44, 'DAY 2 - MT TITLIS', '<p>&nbsp;Mt. Titlis with its beautiful scenery and an adventurous ride up the snow-clad&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Swiss Alps in Rot air - the worlds first revolving cable-car&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;After breakfast &nbsp;in hotel you will visit the world famous Mt. Titles&rsquo;. On a hair&ndash;raising and unforgettable ride to the top of Swiss Alps at 3020 m /10000 ft (30 K.M). You will switch three different cable cars, and be amazed as the scenery changes from green meadows and scenic lakes to snow clad mountains. The last leg of the ride is one of the famous Rot air, which is the world&rsquo;s first revolving cable car, on which you will get an incredibly panoramic view of the surrounding glaciers, mountains and scenery. After lunch we will visit the lake Lucerne, Lion monument .chapel bridge than free time for shopping in Switzerland .After dinner turn back to hotel for overnight stay &nbsp;in Hotel Terrace or similar</p>', '54cc8bba73046day2.jpg'),
(233, 44, ' DAY 03 LIECHTENSTEIN – AUSTRIA', '<p>LIECHTENSTEIN &ndash; AUSTRIA&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;SWAROVSKI CRYSTAL MUSEUM &ndash; TRAIN RIDE IN VADUZ&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;Memorable Train ride in Vaduz&hellip;. .!!!!&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Onto Innsbruck, in picturesque Austria at the crossroads of Europe&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; After the breakfast proceed to Liechtenstein. Liechtenstein is a small, alpine German-speaking country Doubly landlocked by Switzerland and Austria. It is the last remnant of the Holy Roman Empire and an independent nation with very close ties to Switzerland. It enjoys a very high standard of living and is home to some incredibly beautiful mountain scenery. The principalitys capital, Vaduz, is mainly a modern city and a major centre of commerce and international banking. Enjoy your time in train ride in Vaduz. Memorable train ride along the side of Rhine River. After lunch drive to picturesque Austria. Arrive in Innsbruck and proceed for an orientation tour of this beautiful city. Visit the world famous Swarovski Crystal Museum. Enjoy a fascinating experience in to the world of crystals. An experience that leaves you amazed at the dazzling glitter as you walk through this museum. A great opportunity to buy a souvenir for your family. Tonight enjoy a dinner especially prepared for you. Overnight at Hotel Alphotel or similar, in Innsbruck</p>', '54cc8cbd37a28day3.jpg'),
(234, 44, ' DAY 04: VENICE – PADUA', '<p>VENICE &ndash; PADUA &nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;After breakfast transfer from Innsbruck to the Basilica of St. Antony of Padua in Italy. St.Anthony is buried in a chapel within the large Basilica built to honor him, where his tongue is displayed for veneration in a large reliquary. For, when his body was exhumed thirty years after his death, it was claimed that the tongue glistened and looked as if it was still alive and moist; apparently a further claim was made that this was a sign of his gift of preaching. St.Anthony was canonized by Pope Gregory IX on 30 May 1232, at Spoleto, Italy, less than one year after his death. St.Antony is venerated all over the world as the Patron Saint for lost articles, and is credited with many miracles involving lost people, lost things and even lost spiritual goods. The original Basilica of St.Antony was built in 1725 by the local Italian community of Istanbul, but was later demolished and replaced with the current building which was constructed on the same location. The current Basilica was built between 1906 and 1912 in Venetian Neo-Gothic style. Visit St. Mark&rsquo;s Basilica of St.Luke.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>After lunch proceed to Venice. Later enjoy the private boat transfer to the heart of traditional city of Venice, Visit the St.Mark&rsquo;s Square and St.Mark Cathedral. And the tomb of St.Mark inside this basilica. Then we will enjoy a guided walking tour heading to the glass blowing demonstration in Murano Glass Showroom. Overnight stay in Crown Plaza or similar in Padua.</p>', '54cc8ccf5f641day4.jpg'),
(235, 44, 'DAY 5 FLORANCE – PISA', '<p>FLORANCE &ndash; PISA&nbsp;</p>\n<p>After breakfast proceed to Pisa, the wonders of the world The Leaning Tower of Pisa is the campanile, or freestanding bell tower, of the cathedral of the Italian city of Pisa, known worldwide for its unintended tilt to one side. It is situated behind the Cathedral and is the third oldest structure in Pisas Cathedral Square after the Cathedral and the Baptistery. The towers tilt began during construction, caused by an inadequate foundation on ground too soft on one side to properly support the structures weight. The tilt increased in the decades before the structure was completed, and gradually increased until the structure was stabilized (and the tilt partially corrected) by efforts in the late 20th and early 21st centuries. The height of the tower is 55.86 m (183.27 ft) from the ground on the low side and 56.70 m (186.02 ft) on the high side. The width of the walls at the base is 4.09 m (13.42 ft) and at the top 2.48 m (8.14 ft). Its weight is estimated at 14,500 metric tons (16,000 short tons)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;After lunch proceed to Florence. Florence is the birthplace of the Italian language the Renaissance and opera. A guided sightseeing of Florence introduces you to the citys Renaissance splendor. Marvel at Brunelleschis masterpiece&mdash;Florence&rsquo;s massive pink white and green Duomo complemented by Giottos Campanile. Then discover the church of Santa Croce where the tombs of Galileo and Michelangelo as well as the Dante Memorial are displayed. Youll also see the Palazzo Signoria which serves as an open air gallery of ancient and Renaissance statues. Right time turn back to hotel for overnight stay at Hotel Park California or Similar in Florence</p>', '54cc8ce4060e3day5.jpg'),
(236, 44, 'DAY 6 FLORENCE – ROME', '<p>FLORENCE &ndash; ROME</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;Re-live the history of Rome in this ancient citys great landmarks &ndash;Marvel at the Coliseum. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;After breakfast transfer to Rome. Visit the famous Coliseum, St. Mary Major Basilica, Tiber river , Roman Forum, Trevi Fountain , Circus Maximums, Piazza Venezia. Then Monument of Victor Emmanuel II. We also see Arch de Constantine, the Arch of Augustus, The Circus Maximus &amp; other important Roman Monuments. Later enjoy an Indian dinner than turn back to hotel, Overnight stay at Hotel President / Palace / Best Western or similar, in Rome.</p>', '54cc8d2f64d81day6.jpg'),
(237, 44, 'DAY 7: ROME CITY TOUR ', '<p>ROME CITY TOUR&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;Visit the worlds smallest country - the Vatican City which includes the Vatican Museum, the Sistine Chapel and the magnificent St. Peters Basilica.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;After breakfast, proceed for a full day guided city tour of Rome. Vatican is the smallest country in the world or as one says a country within a country. We proceed to St.Peter&rsquo;s Square for Papal Audience. (Subject to the availability of Pope) Papal Audience are held only Wednesdays if the Pope is in Rome, giving pilgrims and visitors the chance to "see the Pope" and receive the Papal Blessing or Apostolic Blessing from the successor of the Apostle Peter during their visit. Then visit Vatican Museum, Sistine Chapel and St.Peter&rsquo;s Basilica. Then visit the St. John Lateran basilica, one of the major Basilicas in Rome. The &lsquo;Scale Santa&rsquo; (Holy steps) located across the street where you may climb the same steps Our Lord climbed on the way to see Pontius Pilate and then visit St.Helena Church to see &lsquo;Santa Cross in Gerusalemme&rsquo; (Holy Cross of Jerusalem), fragments of Holy Cross, One nail, part of the inscription INRI, We owe these valuable relics to St.Helena, the mother of Emperor, Constantine. &amp; other important Roman Monuments. Later enjoy a dinner. in Overnight at Hotel President / Palace / Best Western or similar, in Rome.</p>', '54cc8d4dae5cfday7.jpg'),
(238, 44, 'Day8: Rome- Airport', '<p>Rome- Airport</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Have a very hearty breakfast at the hotel. Pack your bags with a promise to return once again. On time our representative will transfer you to the Airport or Railway Station to board your flight or train with sweet memories of Rome</p>', '54cc8d68c6d7bday8.jpg'),
(239, 45, 'Day 1: Arrive in Rome, Italy', '<p>Arrive in Rome, Italy.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Eurokerala tour director receive you in airport and proceed to your hotel. The rest of the day is free for you to explore this ancient capital city. After dinner turn back to hotel for overnight stay</p>', ''),
(240, 45, 'Day 2: Rome, Vatican city', '<p>Rome, Vatican city</p>\n<p>The&rdquo;Eternal City&rdquo;&mdash;a city steeped in history, vibrantly alive and exciting, and absolutely unique! Included sightseeing with a Local Guide starts in St. Peter&rsquo;s Square, followed by a visit to the Roman Forum and the mighty Colosseum.</p>', ''),
(241, 46, 'Day 1 Monday', '<p>Monday Arrive in Fiumicino airport Rome .An orientation night tour in Roman city .Then overnight stay in Rome</p>', '54cf45cbd120fday1.jpg'),
(242, 46, ' Day 2 Full day city tour ', '<p>After breakfast we proceed to San Giovanni, Santa Scale (Holy step&rsquo;s) San Paolo, Tiber river , Roman Forum,&nbsp; , Circus Maximus, Plaza Venezia. Then Monument of Victor Emmanuel II,&nbsp; Santa Maria Maggiore. Coliseum. Catacomb.&nbsp; and Vatican museum&amp; other important Roman Monuments</p>', '54cf473874332day2.jpg'),
(243, 46, 'Day 3: Vatican—Assisi—Ancona ', '<p>Vatican&mdash;Assisi&mdash;Ancona 310 Km 8.00 Proceed to Vatican Squre for Papa audience&nbsp; After lunch proceed to Assisi where Francis and his companions first came to live in simple huts. It represents the beginning of the Franciscan communities. Other points of big interests: St. Clare Basilica, St. Francis Basilica: centre of the Franciscan spirituality and cradle of the medieval European art, the Basilica was built upon the Saint&rsquo;s tomb.. Then Angona for embark to split overnight stay in cruise ship</p>', '54cf4cf3e8f5bday3.jpg'),
(244, 46, 'Day 4: Split-Medjugorje.', '<p>Split-Medjugorje.145 Km After breakfast aboard our ship, we arrive at the port in the town of Split and depart for Medjugorje. We arrive at St. James Church, the center of spiritual life in Medjugorje, where we celebrate Mass. Following Mass, we visit the Apparitions Hill (Podbrdo) where Our Lady Queen of Peace first appeared to the children. Those who wish to, may climb to the top of Cross Mountain (Krizevak) where the children say that Mary prays at the cross every.&nbsp; In the afternoon we enjoy free time for exploration, personal prayer, confessions and reciting the Rosary.Dinner and overnight stay in Medjugorje</p>', '54cf4a52b4cd6day4.jpg'),
(245, 46, 'Day 5: Medjugorje—Split–Zadar', '<p>Medjugorje&mdash;Split&ndash;Zadar 320 Km Early morning after breakfast proceed to Split an orientation tour in split (Croatia) traveling southeast along the coast to Zadar for sightseeing and an overnight stay. It was under Venetian domination for centuries, then Austro/Hungarian, was ruled by Italy after WWI, and today belongs to Croatia. After dinner overnight stay in Zader</p>', '54cf4c58516d3day5.jpg'),
(246, 46, 'Day 6: Zadar-Plitvice National Park-Zagreb', '<p>Zadar-Plitvice National Park-Zagreb 320Km Plitvice National Park, Croatia. Travel north today back into Croatia to visit the countrys best-known national park"Plitvice. Enjoy a walk with a Local Guide through the breathtaking scenery of this natural wonder. Its 16 lakes, wooded hills, waterfalls, and cascades make it one of Europes most loved national parks. Overnight in Zagreb</p>', '54cf4df11e8feday6.jpg'),
(247, 46, 'Day 7 : Zagreb-Lubliana-postojana-Venice', '<p>Day 7 : Zagreb&mdash;Lubliana&mdash;postojana-Venice 400Km After breakfast proceed to Lubliana castle then Postojana cave&nbsp; the largest cave in the karts region and most visited show cave in all of Europe words on a page can hardly do justice to the majesty of Postojna. So far more than 20 kilometers of galleries have been found of which barely a fraction are open to the public. All the same a visit here still takes up much of a morning or an afternoon as you make your way through the most spectacular parts of the cave at first by a dinky little narrow-gauge train and then on foot. There are no stairs or difficult climbs along the path to or inside the cave so visitors with limited mobility should not have any difficulties&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>After lunch proceed to Venice island<br />Visit the St.Mark&rsquo;s Square and St.Mark Cathedral. And the tomb of St.Mark inside this basilica. Then we will enjoy a guided walking tour in St mark&rsquo;s Square Overnight stay in Venice</p>', '54cf50d32b8ecday7.jpg'),
(248, 46, 'Day 8: St. Antony of Padua-Florence-Pisa tower-Rome', '<p>&nbsp;After breakfast transfer to the Basilica of St. Antony of Padua in Italy. St.Anthony is buried in a chapel within the large Basilica built to honor him, where his tongue is displayed for veneration in a large reliquary. For, when his body was exhumed thirty years after his death, it was claimed that the tongue glistened and looked as if it was still alive and moist; apparently a further claim was made that this was a sign of his gift of preaching. St.Anthony was canonized by Pope Gregory IX on 30 May 1232, at Spoleto, Italy, less than one year after his death. St.Antony is venerated all over the world as the Patron Saint for lost articles, and is credited with many miracles involving lost people, lost things and even lost spiritual goods. The original Basilica of St.Antony was built in 1725 by the local Italian community of Istanbul, but was later demolished and replaced with the current building which was constructed on the same location. The current Basilica was built between 1906 and 1912 in Venetian Neo-Gothic style (one hour time for visit this Basilica)<br />Only an orientation tour in Florence. After proceed to Pisa tower<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; Pisa, the wonders of the world The Leaning Tower of Pisa is the campanile, or freestanding bell tower, of the cathedral of the Italian city of Pisa, known worldwide for its unintended tilt to one side. It is situated behind the Cathedral and is the third oldest structure in Pisas Cathedral Square after the Cathedral and the Baptistery. The towers tilt began during construction, caused by an inadequate <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />foundation on ground too soft on one side to properly support the structures weight. The tilt increased in the decades before the structure was completed, and gradually increased until the structure was stabilized (and the tilt partially corrected) by efforts in the late 20th and early 21st centuries. The height of the tower is 55.86 m (183.27 ft) from the ground on the low side and 56.70 m (186.02 ft) on the high side. The width of the walls at the base is 4.09 m (13.42 ft) and at the top 2.48 m (8.14 ft). Its weight is estimated at 14,500 metric tons (16,000 short tons).overnight stay in Rome</p>', '54cf51553a665day8.jpg'),
(249, 46, 'Day 9 : Airport for return', '<p>Have a very hearty breakfast at the hotel. Pack your bags with a promise to return once again. On time our representative will transfer you to the Airport to board your flight with sweet memories of Europe</p>', '54cf5285915faday9.jpg'),
(250, 47, 'Day 1: HALF DAY CITY TOUR', '<p>15.00&nbsp; Arrive in Fiumicino airport transferred to Roma for half day city tour visit San Giovanni, Santa scale, and&nbsp; Santa Maria Maggiore&nbsp; After dinner proceed to hotel for overnight stay(Depends the arriving timings)Dinner only</p>', '54cf5709e2349day1.jpg'),
(251, 47, 'Day 2: FULL DAY CITY TOUR', '<p>&nbsp;After breakfast St Peter&rsquo;s square, Vatican Museums, Michelangelos breathtaking Sistine Chapel. Stroll through St. Peters Square, passing Berninis famous colonnade, to visit St. Peters Basilica, where you will view Michelangelos Pieta. After lunch, Basilica San Paolo,&nbsp;&nbsp; Coliseum etc.., Overnight stay in Rome (Bf and dinner)</p>', '54cf57d85e4ccday2.jpg'),
(252, 47, 'Day 3: Pisa - FLORENCE', '<p>Pisa the wonders of the World <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After breakfast proceeds to Pisa, the wonders of the world The Leaning Tower of Pisa is the campanile, or freestanding bell tower, of the cathedral of the Italian city of Pisa, known worldwide for its unintended tilt to one side. It is situated behind the Cathedral and is the third oldest structure in Pisas Cathedral Square after the Cathedral and the Baptistery. The towers tilt began during construction, caused by an inadequate foundation on ground too soft on one side to properly support the structures weight. The tilt increased in the decades before the structure was completed, and gradually increased until the structure was stabilized (and the tilt partially corrected) by efforts in the late 20th and early 21st centuries. The height of the tower is 55.86 m (183.27 ft) from the ground on the low side and 56.70 m (186.02 ft) on the high side. The width of the walls at the base is 4.09 m (13.42 ft) and at the top 2.48 m (8.14 ft). Its weight is estimated at 14,500 metric tons (16,000 short tons)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After lunch proceed to Florence. Florence is the birthplace of the Italian language the Renaissance and opera. A guided sightseeing of Florence introduces you to the citys Renaissance splendor. Marvel at Brunelleschi&rsquo;s masterpiece&mdash;Florence&rsquo;s massive pink white and green Duomo complemented by Giotto&rsquo;s Campanile. Then discover the church of Santa Croce where the tombs of Galileo and Michelangelo as well as the Dante Memorial are displayed. You&rsquo;ll also see the Palazzo Signoria which serves as an open air gallery of ancient and Renaissance statues. Right time turn back to hotel for overnight stay at Hotel Park California or Similar in Florence (Bf and dinner)</p>', '54cf58b9c81b7day3.jpg'),
(253, 47, ' Day 4: Florence-Venice city tour', '<p>Florence-Venice city tour 260 km Early morning boat ride to the Island of Murano known throughout the world for its glass manufacturing industry. Visit St. Marks Square to begin a guided walking tour of romantic Venice. View the Golden Basilica of San Marco, the Bridge of Sighs and visit the Doges Palace, whose facade features a massive late-Gothic gate, known as the Porte Della carta , Rest of the day to exploring Venice only your own Optional: Gondola Ride with Music .After lunch proceed to Postojna cave and castle (Slovenia) 200 km<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The largest cave in the karts region and most visited show cave in all of Europe, words on a page can hardly do justice to the majesty of Postojna. So far, more than 20 kilometers of galleries have been found, of which barely a fraction are open to the public. All the same, a visit here still takes up much of a morning or an afternoon, as you make your way through the most spectacular parts of the cave, at first by a dinky little narrow-gauge train, and then on foot. There are no stairs or difficult climbs along the path to or inside the cave, so visitors with limited mobility should not have any difficulties. Overnight stay i Postojna (Bf and dinner)<br /><br /></p>', '54cf5962c19c6day4.jpg'),
(254, 47, 'DAY 5:POSTOJANA—BUDAPEST- HUNGARY', '<p>POSTOJANA&mdash;BUDAPEST- HUNGARY 530 KM After breakfast proceed to&nbsp; Budapest (210km/130miles). Then- see Castle District Hall, Royal palace, Fishermen Bastion, the Holy Trinity square, 1,5 km cave labyrinth. We will cross the Chain Bridge and go from Buda to Pest, we approach the European third largest Parliament. <br />Shopping &amp; leisure time at Vaci street.&nbsp; Lets taste Hungarian cuisine. Overnight stay in Hungary</p>', '54cf59cd85fb0day5.jpg'),
(255, 47, 'DAY6: BUDAPEST – BRATISLAVA', '<p>BUDAPEST &ndash; BRATISLAVA 200Km After breakfast proceed to Bratislava Quality sightseeing tour - see Bratislava castle, Main square &amp; city hall, Slovak National Theatre, Slovak National Gallery...Presidential palace...and war memorial...we combined this sightseeing. And not to forget Petrzalka district, largest housing estate in Central Europe built under the communist regime... Free time for shopping/relaxing/discovering. Little Carpathians tour - well drive north-east of Bratislava (40min drive) to visit a Red Stone castle, magnificent, well-preserved Renaissance/Baroque castle owned by famous families like the Fugger&rsquo;s or the Palfys, then we visit a ceramic factory in Modra, where you can buy an original present, and finish with a professional wine tasting of Slovak wines coming from Small Carpathians wine region.&nbsp; Overnight stay in Bratisalava</p>', '54cf5a6ee5fb3day6.jpg'),
(256, 47, 'Day 7: BRATISLAVA - BRNO - PRAGUE, CZECH REPUBLIC', '<p>BRATISLAVA - BRNO - PRAGUE, CZECH REPUBLIC, 350 Km Transfer to Prague. We will stop in Brno ( 130km/70miles) - the second largest city in Czech republic, where we have lunch, a short sightseeing tour, see Spielberg Castle, St. Peters &amp; Pauls Cathedral, Main square &amp; free time for shopping. Then we continue to Prague (from Brno it is 200km/120miles). Then we&nbsp; See Hradcany castle, Lesser town, famous gothic Charles Bridge which connects the Old Town and Mala Strana, Jewish Synagogues, Old Town square &amp; magnificent Old Town Hall and the famous clock, hourly showing 12 apostles. <br />Our tour ends in Wenceslavs Square, centre of entertainment, lots of shopping streets and restaurants. Prague - has various names such as mother of cities, gold city or city of hundred spices. Overnight stay in Prague.</p>', '54cf5b3120c60day7.jpg'),
(257, 47, 'DAY 8: PRAGUE-VIENNA, AUSTRIA 350 km', '<p>Transfer to Vienna, Austria. Lunch break and quality sightseeing tour around the Old City. See Stephans square, Stephans Cathedral, the Parliament, the imperial palace Hofburg, Staatsoper &amp; Burgtheater Then there is a must what every traveller coming to Vienna should try - Vienna coffee ( Wiener Kaffee) and Sacher cake ( Sacher Torte ). Delicious. <br />A typical food is Wienerschnitzel (pork meat), why not to try it.. Overnight stay in Vienna</p>', '54cf5ca0c0fa7day8.jpg'),
(258, 47, 'DAY9: VIENNA -AIRPORT', '<p>Have a very hearty breakfast at the hotel. Pack your bags with a promise to return once again. On time transfer you to the Airport to board your flight with sweet memories of Europe</p>', '54cf5ce11d157day9.jpg'),
(259, 48, 'Day:1', '<p>Arrive in Fiumicino airport&nbsp; Rome&rsquo; Then we will visit Vatican museum ,Basilica St Peter, Castel Santa Angelo. Hill Genicolense. Vatican square. After dinner proceed to hotel for overnight stay</p>', '54cf63a05ccadday1.jpg'),
(260, 48, 'Day:2', '<p>After breakfast proceed to San Giovanni, Holly steps. Coliseum. Circo Maximo,Roman fourm. Catacomb. San Paolo, Piazza Venezia .Piazza del popolo etc.. Overnight stay in Rome</p>', '54cf63e232312day2.jpg'),
(261, 48, 'Day:3 Also in Rome', '<p>An orientation tour in city with shopping</p>', '54cf649e056d1day3.jpg'),
(262, 48, 'Day:4 Florence-Pisa ', '<p>&nbsp;Florence-Pisa 360Km After breakfast Proceed to Florence we will visit Piazza Signoria, two meusums(optional)Mickle Angelo&rsquo;s famous statue David than Piazza Mickle Angelo (The top of the hill)<br />Then proceed to Pisa (The leaning tower of Pisa)&nbsp;&nbsp; Overnight stay in Pisa</p>', '54cf68f159972day4.jpg'),
(263, 48, 'Day :5 Pisa-Padua–Venice', '<p>Florence&mdash;Pisa 360Km After breakfast Proceed to Florence we will visit Piazza Signoria, two meusums(optional)Mickle Angelo&rsquo;s famous statue David than Piazza Mickle Angelo (The top of the hill)<br />Then proceed to Pisa (The leaning tower of Pisa)&nbsp;&nbsp; Overnight stay in Pisa</p>', '54cf66f79f60cday5.jpg'),
(264, 48, 'Day :5 Pisa-Padua–Venice', '<p>Day :5 Pisa-Padua&ndash;Venice Km 260&nbsp; Padoawe will Visit St Antonys church. and tomb&nbsp; then Venice<br />Rest of the full day in Venice island visit St mark square grant canal etc</p>', '54cf68b072b6bday5.jpg'),
